  <p class="mt-2">The "Unsold Homes" category is critical. It represents a stalled development pipelineâ€”homes built at a price point the general population can no longer afford.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">What to Watch For</h3>
  <p>To see the core feedback loop, try this: set the <strong>Landlord Cap</strong> high (e.g., 45%) and run the simulation for 30+ years. You will likely see:</p>
  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li>Landlords use their "cash offer" advantage to acquire more property, increasing their <strong>Concentration</strong>.</li>
      <li>This concentration suppresses the <strong>New Home Approval Rate</strong>.</li>
      <li>The lack of new supply causes the <strong>Seeking Housing</strong> pool to swell.</li>
      <li>The huge number of seekers causes <strong>Median Home Price</strong> and <strong>Median Rent</strong> to skyrocket, completely detaching from incomes.</li>
      <li>This results in a "failed market" with high vacancy, high prices, and a massive population unable to find a home.</li>
  </ol>
